    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Central Park Terror: The Outcry</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas Love letter on mob assault in Central Park against women; questions whether mobs of hoodlums would have been as aggressive if they had known that some of their prey might be legally armed and able to defend themselves</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani hit the nail on the head with his comment about the mob attacks on women in Central Park on Sunday evening. You quote him as saying (front page, June 13), ''It is unrealistic to assume that police officers can be everywhere at all times.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani hit the nail on the head with his comment about the mob attacks on women in Central Park on Sunday evening. You quote him as saying (front page, June 13), ''It is unrealistic to assume that police officers can be everywhere at all times.''</p>
        <p>That is true, but does anyone think that the mobs of hoodlums roaming Central Park and sexually assaulting women would have been as aggressive if they had known that some of their prey might be legally armed and able to defend themselves?</p>
        <p>THOMAS LOVE  McLean, Va., June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
